To get a good base, I experimented with
the number of nodes,the activation functions and optimizers.
First, tried 3 layers with high number of nodes, and noticed that a complex model
with optimizer SGD was not better than one with less in the first layer;
both performed good on training and were a bit overfitting. The same setting with different
optimizers lowered the performance. Since performance improved and overfitting
did not become greater with a 4th layer I kept it to further regularize.

generalization imporved; the loss is minimized along the trainig, but the trend is similar the validation too.

Focused on convolution layers onnly of 9x9 and 3x3 filter. To make it
learn the training data with a high accuracy but to generalize
well I added batchnormalizer after every block of convolutional layers.
Whenever the number of filters is doubled, a further maxpooling layer of 2x2 filter is added and combined with a 20% dropout.
This arrangement of convolutional and regularizer layers in the end is connected 
with one Dense layer followed by normalization

Augmenting in this case is difficult as the images are low resolution.
Strong rotation and sheer destroyed too much information and lead to a decay in performance.
In the misclassified images I noticed that a reason for not recognizing correctly is due to
the numbers being shifted to the edge. Thus, I added small width and height shifts.
I got improvement of 2-3% with very small augmentation. This lead to lower validation loss
along training loss, showing that my model is doing good.

Answer 3.1 (2p)¶

Accuracy:  0.9507
[247, 491, 570, 603, 660]

The test accuracy is 0.9494 which is between the training and validation accuracy
indicating that my model is stable and generalises well on unseen data.
According to the confusion matrix the number 1 and 7 was misclassified the most often, thus I
focused on plotting the number 7. Majority of the mistakes
are made for this class and the confusion is often with the two other most often misclassifed classes: 1 and 2.
The errors are noticable on the plotted samples as those are mostly related to the noise or shift in image.
As some parts of the numbers are outside of the image indicates that a shift in the data augmentation is needed.
In case the image is blurry the misclassification targets the numbers 1 and 2,
but when an image is shifted we can see that the misclassification is happening due to another number visible in the image.

The convolutional part fully frozen is performing poorly on this dataset which is due to the fact that it has been trained on different dataset.
Unfreezing the last convolutional block the performance increases, and connected with a Dense layer with small regularization this has been improved to 0.85 and 0.82.
Tried unfreezing the last block layer by layer, but the best seemed to be unfreezing the whole block and retraining that for this task.
